Part I: Dummy & Contrast Coding

The data set entitled Read.xlsx contains end-of-year reading comprehension scores (readcomp) for 66 1st graders. Children were randomly assigned to one of three classrooms (group): CONTROL (group = 1; no reading comprehension instruction), READ1 (group = 2; standard reading comprehension instruction), and READ2 (group = 3; a new reading program). The goal of this research was to determine whether, in terms of end-of-year reading comprehension scores, READ2 was better than READ1, and if both READ1 and READ2 were better than the CONTROL condition. All students were tested at baseline and it was found that there were no significant differences in reading comprehension among the three groups. Please complete the following exercises using this data set:

Interpretation:

When reference category= CONTROL

The Estimate column in the output table shows the coefficients for the dummy-coded variables relative to the reference group (CONTROL). For example, the coefficient for READ1 is 5.68, which means that, on average, the effect of READ1 have 5.68 unit more than the CONTROL group (the reference group). Similarly, the coefficient for READ2 is 3.23, which means that, on average, he effect of READ2 have 3.23 unit more than the CONTROL group.

When reference category= READ1

The Estimate column in the output table shows the coefficients for the dummy-coded variables relative to the reference group (READ1). For example, the coefficient for CONTROL is -5.68, which means that, on average, the effect of CONTROL have 5.68 unit less than the READ1 group (the reference group). Similarly, the coefficient for READ2 is -2.45, which means that, on average, he effect of READ2 have 2.45 unit less than the READ1 group.

When reference category= READ2

The Estimate column in the output table shows the coefficients for the dummy-coded variables relative to the reference group (READ2). For example, the coefficient for CONTROL is -3.23, which means that, on average, the effect of CONTROL have 3.23 unit less than the READ2 group (the reference group). Similarly, the coefficient for READ1 is 2.45, which means that, on average, he effect of READ1 have 2.45 unit more than the READ2 group.

Overall fit for the model remains the same, F(2,63) = 4.48, p = 0.02, R² = 0.12 and Adj. R² = 0.10 . For a categorical variable in regression analysis, R² = 0.12 means that the model explains 12% of the variance in the dependent variable that can be attributed to the categorical variable.

  1. If you had to pick one type of coding method to BEST address the research questions above, which would you choose and why?

    The choice between dummy coding and contrast coding depends on the specific research question and the nature of the categorical variable. Dummy coding is often the default method used in regression analysis and is appropriate when the research question focuses on differences between specific categories and a clear reference category can be identified. Contrast coding is more appropriate when the research question is focused on comparing groups of categories or testing specific hypotheses about the effects of the categorical variable.
    The goal of this research was to determine whether, in terms of end-of-year reading comprehension scores, READ2 was better than READ1, and if both READ1 and READ2 were better than the CONTROL condition. From this, we can understand that this research question is focused on comparing groups of categories (READ1 vs READ2) and (READ1 & READ2 vs CONTROL).Therefore, I will choose contrast coding method instead of dummy coding method.

3. Given that removing influential data is an extreme step, and that robust regression methods are a compromise approach, which model(s) would you select for inclusion in your final research report? Why? There is no right or wrong answer here, as is often the case in statistics.

I would take robust regression methods as it is the most accurate in predicting the outcome variable than a model that takes into account influential data points. I think, removing them can lead to a loss of information and potential bias in the model. So, a robust regression method, such as the Huber regression may be a suitable compromise to balance the need for accuracy with the need to account for influential data.
